Here's breakfast.

22
00:04:18,791 --> 00:04:22,290
No time. I'll get fired.

23
00:04:22,708 --> 00:04:25,873
Serves you right.
If you kept a few shirts here,

24
00:04:26,208 --> 00:04:28,790
you'd save a whole hour.

25
00:04:29,333 --> 00:04:32,165
- I also need a razor.
- Use mine.

26
00:04:32,333 --> 00:04:35,123
I like my own razor.

27
00:04:35,291 --> 00:04:37,623
What do you need a razor for?

28
00:04:38,791 --> 00:04:41,165
Don't tell me. I'd rather not know.

29
00:04:43,749 --> 00:04:47,373
A normal man, if you know what I mean,

30
00:04:47,874 --> 00:04:52,582
who sleeps with a woman,
who enjoys sleeping with him. . .

31
00:04:52,958 --> 00:04:56,332
If this normal man
brought his razor and his clothes along,

32
00:04:56,499 --> 00:04:59,248
they'd save a fortune in rent!

33
00:04:59,416 --> 00:05:02,373
Many perfectly normal people

34
00:05:02,541 --> 00:05:04,998
are creatures of habit.

35
00:05:05,166 --> 00:05:06,540
Some are maniacs!

36
00:05:06,708 --> 00:05:09,082
You're an old maniac, very old !

37
00:05:14,041 --> 00:05:16,165
True, I'm old. But the elderly

38
00:05:16,916 --> 00:05:18,832
have wisdom.

39
00:05:19,916 --> 00:05:21,748
Your friend's watch. . .

40
00:05:22,958 --> 00:05:24,248
You fixed it?

41
00:05:24,416 --> 00:05:26,998
It needs a real watchmaker.

42
00:05:27,166 --> 00:05:30,207
Digital watches are beyond me.

43
00:05:30,374 --> 00:05:31,665
Never mind.

44
00:05:31,833 --> 00:05:34,332
I've got a present for you.

45
00:05:40,916 --> 00:05:42,623
Léautaud's Diaries!

46
00:05:42,999 --> 00:05:46,498
You found all 1 9 volumes?

47
00:05:47,749 --> 00:05:50,582
He had nothing but problems with women.

48
00:05:51,624 --> 00:05:52,998
Poor Léautaud !

49
00:05:54,166 --> 00:05:57,123
I'll tell you why.

50
00:05:57,791 --> 00:05:59,707
He wanted to make love to his mother.

51
00:05:59,874 --> 00:06:03,457
She didn't mind, but nothing ever happened.

52
00:06:04,499 --> 00:06:07,582
Anyway, thanks for his diaries.

53
00:06:07,749 --> 00:06:09,207
You're nicer than I thought.

54
00:06:17,708 --> 00:06:20,707
May I put my hand there?

55
00:06:21,166 --> 00:06:23,165
If you promise to keep it there.

56
00:06:25,749 --> 00:06:29,207
I switched vacations with Emmanuel.

57
00:06:29,374 --> 00:06:30,957
We can leave on July 31 .

58
00:06:31,124 --> 00:06:33,832
So close the shop. We'll take off together.

59
00:06:33,999 --> 00:06:34,998
To the country.

60
00:06:35,166 --> 00:06:37,248
We'll drink warm milk, fresh from the cow!

61
00:06:37,458 --> 00:06:39,082
Yuck!

62
00:06:47,291 --> 00:06:48,790
My friend, Zenaida,

63
00:06:49,124 --> 00:06:50,832
has invited us

64
00:06:50,999 --> 00:06:54,623
to her housewarming.
I said we'd go. Is that okay?

65
00:06:54,999 --> 00:06:58,040
Sure, with pleasure! See you tonight.

66
00:07:41,333 --> 00:07:43,707
Your phone's been busy for an hour!

67
00:07:43,874 --> 00:07:45,957
I know. What is it?

68
00:07:46,124 --> 00:07:48,165
You crazy? Have you forgotten?

69
00:07:48,333 --> 00:07:49,373
Good God!

70
00:07:49,458 --> 00:07:51,748
Our divorce decree.
We must sign it in an hour.

71
00:07:51,916 --> 00:07:54,582
- Hurry!
- I'm shaving.

72
00:07:54,749 --> 00:07:56,415
Come unshaven.

73
00:07:56,583 --> 00:07:58,873
No, I'll pick you up in a cab.

74
00:07:59,041 --> 00:08:00,248
Alphonse wants a word,

75
00:08:00,416 --> 00:08:03,290
but keep it short.

76
00:08:04,374 --> 00:08:05,665
Hey, Dad?

77
00:08:05,833 --> 00:08:08,165
Can you take me to the station
for our class trip?

78
00:08:08,333 --> 00:08:09,415
What time?

79
00:08:09,583 --> 00:08:11,498
I don't know. Here's Mom.

80
00:08:12,291 --> 00:08:14,165
He must be there by 7 p.m.

81
00:08:14,333 --> 00:08:16,498
I can't take him. I'm working.

82
00:08:16,666 --> 00:08:18,498
I'm going to a party.

83
00:08:18,666 --> 00:08:21,332
Cancel it. Alphonse needs you.

84
00:08:22,958 --> 00:08:24,248
Okay. I'll be there.

85
00:08:32,791 --> 00:08:36,248
I've got two seats for the Shapiro concert.

86
00:08:36,416 --> 00:08:37,998
Want to come?

87
00:08:38,166 --> 00:08:41,457
I'm busy. Do you want Paul Simon?
If not, I'll put him away!

88
00:08:41,624 --> 00:08:43,415
First, I want to listen.

89
00:08:43,583 --> 00:08:46,498
In the booth. What a creep!

90
00:08:53,749 --> 00:08:57,707
I'm sorry, no time to explain.

91
00:08:58,249 --> 00:08:59,873
I can't go to the party tonight.

92
00:09:00,041 --> 00:09:01,957
We can get there late.

93
00:09:02,208 --> 00:09:04,207
I can't make it.

94
00:09:04,666 --> 00:09:06,665
Why? Stop panting !

95
00:09:06,833 --> 00:09:09,832
I can't explain now.

96
00:09:09,999 --> 00:09:11,665
Someone's waiting for me.

97
00:09:12,458 --> 00:09:14,540
I'll call you from the print shop.

98
00:09:17,499 --> 00:09:21,082
How could you forget our divorce?

99
00:09:21,291 --> 00:09:23,665
No one would believe it.

100
00:09:23,833 --> 00:09:26,332
The incredible is often true.

101
00:09:27,124 --> 00:09:30,082
I bet you've forgotten our wedding date.

102
00:09:30,249 --> 00:09:32,540
February 26!

103
00:09:32,708 --> 00:09:34,082
You actually remember!

104
00:09:34,249 --> 00:09:36,332
It's Saint Nestor's Day.

105
00:09:36,499 --> 00:09:38,207
Of course.

106
00:09:43,833 --> 00:09:45,540
- Why the violin?
- For a lesson.

107
00:09:45,708 --> 00:09:47,665
You're giving a lesson at this hour?

108
00:09:49,374 --> 00:09:51,040
So that's your violin !

109
00:09:51,208 --> 00:09:53,707
It's so I can stay in a hotel tonight.

110
00:09:53,874 --> 00:09:56,457
Stay here. I'll sleep in the chair.

111
00:09:56,624 --> 00:09:58,332
You can have the bed.

112
00:09:58,499 --> 00:10:00,623
No, not in the same room as you !

113
00:10:00,791 --> 00:10:04,415
Have it your way. Not in the same room.

114
00:10:20,874 --> 00:10:23,332
lmagine printing this in a newspaper.

115
00:10:24,083 --> 00:10:25,707
Listen to this. It's about

116
00:10:25,874 --> 00:10:29,665
the Common Market convention
in Brussels. It says,

117
00:10:30,083 --> 00:10:33,957
"At 1 2 p.m. the delegates retired
to their rooms. Each man

118
00:10:34,124 --> 00:10:37,248
"was provided with a girl in the sack."

119
00:10:37,416 --> 00:10:38,582
I don't believe it.

120
00:10:38,749 --> 00:10:42,707
It's true! lmagine reading that in Le Monde.

121
00:10:43,166 --> 00:10:47,707
"Each man was provided
with a girl in the sack."

122
00:10:48,208 --> 00:10:50,457
- You're lying.
- Read it yourself.

123
00:10:52,958 --> 00:10:55,332
"The delegates retired to their rooms.

124
00:10:55,499 --> 00:10:59,623
"Each man was provided
with a midnight snack." You idiot!

125
00:11:13,833 --> 00:11:17,540
Mrs Christine Doinel is next.

126
00:11:17,708 --> 00:11:19,540
What about me?

127
00:11:19,916 --> 00:11:21,290
Must be a mistake.

128
00:11:21,458 --> 00:11:24,665
No, it's normal procedure.

129
00:11:24,833 --> 00:11:25,873
Come, hurry.

130
00:11:29,374 --> 00:11:31,207
We'll wait here.

131
00:11:38,333 --> 00:11:41,248
I can't stay long.
I'm meeting some friends later.

132
00:11:41,416 --> 00:11:42,748
Do you mind?

133
00:11:42,916 --> 00:11:44,623
Not at all.

134
00:11:45,041 --> 00:11:48,582
- You're sure now?
- I don't mind at all.

135
00:11:48,999 --> 00:11:50,540
If you did, would you tell me?

136
00:11:50,708 --> 00:11:54,373
No, I wouldn't. But I really don't mind.

137
00:12:10,458 --> 00:12:13,915
Mr Doinel, to the Judge's Chambers.

138
00:12:22,874 --> 00:12:24,332
Please be seated.

139
00:12:24,999 --> 00:12:27,040
I'm seeing you separately

140
00:12:27,208 --> 00:12:29,873
to make sure you both reached your decision

141
00:12:30,041 --> 00:12:32,332
freely and without coercion.

142
00:12:32,749 --> 00:12:34,332
Since our first meeting

143
00:12:34,499 --> 00:12:36,832
three months ago,
you've had time to consider

144
00:12:37,249 --> 00:12:39,457
the consequences of your act.

145
00:12:40,291 --> 00:12:41,873
Until very recently,

146
00:12:42,041 --> 00:12:46,373
to get a divorce, you had to produce
abusive letters from your spouse.

147
00:12:46,916 --> 00:12:49,415
What if they hadn't written any?

148
00:12:49,583 --> 00:12:52,415
I'd make some up and they'd copy them.

149
00:13:02,249 --> 00:13:04,748
Can you reach that bottle?

150
00:13:09,458 --> 00:13:11,290
You've forgotten?

151
00:13:19,416 --> 00:13:22,915
Mrs Doinel to the Judge's Chambers.

152
00:13:40,249 --> 00:13:42,998
I'll now read the clauses of the Settlement.

153
00:13:43,499 --> 00:13:45,248
"Names of the parties:

154
00:13:45,416 --> 00:13:48,998
"Mrs Doinel reverts to her maiden
name of Christine Darbon."

155
00:13:49,541 --> 00:13:53,123
At first, you wanted to keep
your married name

156
00:13:53,291 --> 00:13:54,290
because of your son.

157
00:13:55,583 --> 00:13:58,873
We've talked it over with Alphonse,
haven't we?

158
00:14:01,041 --> 00:14:03,165
He understands.

159
00:14:03,333 --> 00:14:04,957
He doesn't mind at all.

160
00:14:05,374 --> 00:14:08,665
"Child Custody and Support:

161
00:14:08,833 --> 00:14:11,623
"By mutual agreement the mother
will have custody of the child.

162
00:14:11,791 --> 00:14:13,707
"The father is granted visitation rights

163
00:14:13,874 --> 00:14:16,332
"and may provide lodging for a period

164
00:14:16,541 --> 00:14:20,498
"not in excess of half the annual vacation.

165
00:14:20,666 --> 00:14:22,457
"Mr Doinel will pay Mrs Doinel

166
00:14:22,624 --> 00:14:28,415
"as his share of child support
a monthly alimony of 900 francs

167
00:14:28,749 --> 00:14:31,290
"until such time as the child
is self-supporting."

168
00:14:31,958 --> 00:14:33,248
Please.

169
00:14:37,624 --> 00:14:40,373
I will now read you the full Decree.

170
00:14:41,083 --> 00:14:43,623
If I ask you for a favour, will you do it?

171
00:14:43,791 --> 00:14:45,207
That depends.

172
00:14:45,874 --> 00:14:46,873
Quibbling again !

173
00:14:47,749 --> 00:14:49,082
Will you do it?

174
00:14:49,249 --> 00:14:50,957
Try me.

175
00:14:51,916 --> 00:14:53,998
Put your glasses on again.

176
00:15:06,291 --> 00:15:08,082
"As judge of the Family Court

177
00:15:08,249 --> 00:15:10,998
"I hereby declare that

178
00:15:11,166 --> 00:15:13,748
"Antoine Doinel and Christine Doinel,

179
00:15:13,916 --> 00:15:18,040
"née Darbon, born in Dijon, March 1 2, 1 951

180
00:15:18,583 --> 00:15:22,207
"upon their joint petition,
are granted a divorce.

181
00:15:22,374 --> 00:15:24,623
"The settlement stipulates that

182
00:15:24,791 --> 00:15:27,040
"both parties will bear the costs.

183
00:15:27,208 --> 00:15:30,873
"If they fail to agree on the terms

184
00:15:31,041 --> 00:15:32,957
"said costs will be equally divided."

185
00:15:34,499 --> 00:15:35,540
No signatures?

186
00:15:41,416 --> 00:15:43,290
What's all this?

187
00:15:43,458 --> 00:15:44,998
I knew it! The press!

188
00:15:45,166 --> 00:15:47,748
You're the first divorce under the new law.

189
00:15:47,916 --> 00:15:48,915
Don't go!

190
00:15:49,041 --> 00:15:51,540
Pictures! Hope they'll give us a few.

191
00:15:51,708 --> 00:15:52,998
Funny!

192
00:15:53,166 --> 00:15:55,748
Let's make a good impression.

193
00:16:04,333 --> 00:16:06,540
You don't say hello?

194
00:16:07,333 --> 00:16:08,415
How are you?

195
00:16:08,583 --> 00:16:10,165
- It's so nice to see you.
- You too.

196
00:16:10,333 --> 00:16:11,915
See our debate on TV?

197
00:16:12,083 --> 00:16:14,957
That prosecutor overdid it.

198
00:16:15,208 --> 00:16:16,665
The law isn't so new.

199
00:16:16,833 --> 00:16:20,457
It dates back to the Revolution.
Right, Antoine?

200
00:16:20,624 --> 00:16:21,623
Leave me out of it.

201
00:16:21,749 --> 00:16:24,790
The lawyer assigned to the case.

202
00:16:25,749 --> 00:16:27,957
I know that guy.

203
00:16:28,499 --> 00:16:29,915
He's Antoine Doinel.

204
00:16:30,666 --> 00:16:34,207
I met him years ago, at a Youth Concert.

205
00:16:34,374 --> 00:16:37,165
I was impressed.
He had his own flat and a job

206
00:16:37,333 --> 00:16:40,040
with a record company. Real independent!

207
00:16:41,874 --> 00:16:44,998
He's a client. Rather, his wife is.

208
00:16:45,166 --> 00:16:48,957
They just got a divorce under the new law.

209
00:16:49,124 --> 00:16:52,498
I can't believe it. Antoine divorced !

210
00:16:53,083 --> 00:16:57,165
Does that call for
condolences or congratulations?

211
00:16:58,249 --> 00:17:02,665
Napoleon used the law to dump Josephine.

212
00:17:02,833 --> 00:17:05,873
Are you going to take
on the Draguignan case?

213
00:17:06,374 --> 00:17:08,915
My friends tell me it's a nasty business.

214
00:17:09,083 --> 00:17:10,498
But I'm tempted.

215
00:17:10,666 --> 00:17:13,207
Take your friends' advice. They're right.

216
00:17:13,374 --> 00:17:15,707
It's a messy case.

217
00:17:16,749 --> 00:17:18,832
Still, I'd like to see the whole file.

218
00:17:18,999 --> 00:17:21,415
That's why I'm going
to Aix-en-Provence tonight.

219
00:17:21,791 --> 00:17:23,915
Well then, good luck!

220
00:17:24,083 --> 00:17:25,540
I'll need it.

221
00:17:26,499 --> 00:17:28,873
Always running. Hasn't changed a bit!

222
00:17:45,541 --> 00:17:48,123
Watch out for your suit!

223
00:17:52,958 --> 00:17:55,873
In your Sunday best. Been to a wedding?

224
00:17:56,041 --> 00:17:58,873
No, not a wedding. In fact, just the opposite!

225
00:18:00,083 --> 00:18:02,457
- Your digital watch.
- Did she fix it?

226
00:18:02,624 --> 00:18:05,082
- She couldn't.
- Too bad.

227
00:18:05,249 --> 00:18:07,623
- What's this?
- A rush job.

228
00:18:07,791 --> 00:18:09,748
I did half to help you out.

229
00:18:09,916 --> 00:18:12,707
Here are the last pages.

230
00:18:12,874 --> 00:18:14,915
You're a real pal !

231
00:18:31,083 --> 00:18:33,748
I'm fed up. Too many problems.

232
00:18:34,499 --> 00:18:37,123
What good is a divorce if you always wind up

233
00:18:37,416 --> 00:18:39,498
with the same kind of girl?

234
00:18:39,666 --> 00:18:41,373
I bet the new one's just like the old one.

235
00:18:41,541 --> 00:18:43,623
You only fall for nice girls.

236
00:18:44,916 --> 00:18:46,790
The truth of the matter is,

237
00:18:46,958 --> 00:18:49,540
I don't just fall for the girl.

238
00:18:49,708 --> 00:18:52,957
I fall for the whole family: father, mother. . .

239
00:18:53,124 --> 00:18:54,415
I like girls with nice parents.

240
00:18:54,583 --> 00:18:57,332
Is Sabine tall or short?

241
00:18:58,208 --> 00:19:01,498
In between, about up to here.

242
00:19:01,666 --> 00:19:05,582
I remember when
you only went out with tall girls.

243
00:19:06,083 --> 00:19:07,332
Very tall.

244
00:19:07,499 --> 00:19:10,790
I liked them at least a head taller.

245
00:19:26,708 --> 00:19:29,957
Does the name Doinel ring a bell?

246
00:19:31,083 --> 00:19:34,873
Antoine Doinel.
His novel came out two years ago.

247
00:19:35,041 --> 00:19:36,582
You wanted a Dalloz.

248
00:19:36,749 --> 00:19:39,248
I still do, but that's not the one.

249
00:19:39,416 --> 00:19:43,123
I also want a novel written by Antoine Doinel.

250
00:19:43,291 --> 00:19:46,165
One thing at a time. First, which Dalloz?

251
00:19:46,333 --> 00:19:48,998
His book on child-murderers.

252
00:19:49,166 --> 00:19:53,082
It's that case in Draguignan. I'm in a spot.

253
00:19:54,166 --> 00:19:56,623
I see you couldn't care less!

254
00:19:58,624 --> 00:19:59,957
Listen, Colette.

255
00:20:01,624 --> 00:20:03,998
In here, you're just another customer.

256
00:20:04,166 --> 00:20:05,457
Thanks!

257
00:20:05,624 --> 00:20:07,998
Well, to me, you're much more
than a salesman !

258
00:20:08,166 --> 00:20:09,998
Don't I know it!

259
00:20:11,208 --> 00:20:14,582
I wish you'd stop carrying on about nothing.

260
00:20:14,749 --> 00:20:16,873
It's for you, Mr Xavier.

261
00:20:22,458 --> 00:20:23,957
Sabine. . .

262
00:20:24,333 --> 00:20:26,582
I can't tonight. Is tomorrow all right?

263
00:20:28,124 --> 00:20:29,873
See you then, my dear Sabine.

264
00:20:33,749 --> 00:20:35,957
If I'm not mistaken,

265
00:20:36,124 --> 00:20:38,290
Sabine is a girl's name.

266
00:20:38,874 --> 00:20:40,832
That's right.

267
00:20:42,249 --> 00:20:44,707
Well, I'm sorry to bother you
by buying books

268
00:20:44,874 --> 00:20:47,457
in your very own bookstore.

269
00:20:47,624 --> 00:20:49,082
Now I remember.

270
00:20:49,249 --> 00:20:51,957
The title of that book had the word

271
00:20:52,124 --> 00:20:54,332
"Love" in it. Yes, I said "Love!"

272
00:20:54,499 --> 00:20:57,707
Then try a second-hand bookstore.

273
00:20:58,333 --> 00:20:59,748
Listen to me!

274
00:20:59,916 --> 00:21:02,457
The titles I sell don't have the word "Love."

275
00:21:02,624 --> 00:21:04,707
He's incredible!

276
00:21:05,874 --> 00:21:07,582
What a bastard !

277
00:21:07,749 --> 00:21:09,415
Love And Other Troubles.

278
00:21:09,583 --> 00:21:11,207
That's it!

279
00:21:12,916 --> 00:21:14,457
Let's see your bread.

280
00:21:17,833 --> 00:21:19,623
You ate some.

281
00:21:19,916 --> 00:21:21,748
Come over here.

282
00:21:28,166 --> 00:21:29,498
Put that down.

283
00:21:33,541 --> 00:21:34,998
Right or left?

284
00:21:35,874 --> 00:21:37,582
The left, sir.

285
00:21:43,124 --> 00:21:44,748
How much do I owe you?

286
00:21:44,916 --> 00:21:46,457
39 francs.

287
00:21:48,749 --> 00:21:52,623
Xavier's so handsome.
He looks like Napoleon.

288
00:21:56,249 --> 00:21:58,248
I'm so glad to have this book.

289
00:21:58,416 --> 00:22:00,082
I can read it tonight.

290
00:22:00,249 --> 00:22:04,248
The train for Aix-en-Provence
leaving at 7:02 p.m. , platform 1 5

291
00:22:04,708 --> 00:22:06,123
Gare de Lyon.

292
00:22:47,249 --> 00:22:49,290
Stay there.

293
00:23:07,208 --> 00:23:08,498
I'm at the station.

294
00:23:08,583 --> 00:23:09,623
What for?

295
00:23:09,833 --> 00:23:12,415
I'd forgotten a very important date.

296
00:23:12,583 --> 00:23:14,082
I'll explain later.

297
00:23:14,249 --> 00:23:16,207
You promised to come tonight.

298
00:23:16,374 --> 00:23:19,332
I didn't know about Alphonse's trip.

299
00:23:19,499 --> 00:23:21,040
I'm with him now at the station.

300
00:23:21,208 --> 00:23:24,290
I could have come. To meet your son.

301
00:23:24,458 --> 00:23:25,457
I'm dying to.

302
00:23:25,791 --> 00:23:26,915
lsn't it high time?

303
00:23:27,083 --> 00:23:30,207
Not right now. It might upset him.

304
00:23:30,374 --> 00:23:32,415
You're so complicated.

305
00:23:32,583 --> 00:23:35,832
Ask your wife, your ex-wife.

306
00:23:36,166 --> 00:23:38,873
You know I lead an orderly life.

307
00:23:39,041 --> 00:23:40,040
I can't change overnight.

308
00:23:40,124 --> 00:23:43,832
I'm fed up with your mania for secrecy.

309
00:23:43,999 --> 00:23:46,582
Alphonse meets too many outsiders.

310
00:23:47,249 --> 00:23:49,290
"Outsiders." Thanks a lot!

311
00:23:49,541 --> 00:23:52,498
If you take me for a hooker,

312
00:23:52,666 --> 00:23:54,248
then pay me each time we make love.

313
00:23:55,124 --> 00:23:56,540
You're not being funny.

314
00:23:56,708 --> 00:23:59,832
Look, maybe you can afford to waste time.

315
00:23:59,999 --> 00:24:02,832
The train won't wait. Neither will my work.

316
00:24:02,999 --> 00:24:05,623
I've got no time

317
00:24:05,791 --> 00:24:08,623
to fool around on the phone.
I'm hanging up.

318
00:24:34,374 --> 00:24:36,123
That's your coach, I think.

319
00:24:36,208 --> 00:24:37,957
Run, my son !

320
00:24:40,541 --> 00:24:42,707
Be nice to little girls.

321
00:24:44,749 --> 00:24:46,290
Give your daddy a kiss.

322
00:24:49,083 --> 00:24:50,832
Hold on, Dad !

323
00:24:51,249 --> 00:24:52,248
I am.

324
00:24:53,583 --> 00:24:55,165
Take care.

325
00:24:58,083 --> 00:24:59,248
Which one is mine?

326
00:24:59,416 --> 00:25:01,457
Number 51 .

327
00:25:02,874 --> 00:25:04,082
When does the train leave?

328
00:25:04,166 --> 00:25:05,207
In six minutes.

329
00:25:05,291 --> 00:25:06,332
Is there a diner?

330
00:25:06,541 --> 00:25:08,165
It's up front.

331
00:25:09,208 --> 00:25:10,748
When does it leave?

332
00:25:11,624 --> 00:25:13,290
Your train leaves very soon.

333
00:25:14,249 --> 00:25:16,582
In exactly 1 5 minutes.

334
00:25:19,083 --> 00:25:20,498
I bet that woman's a spy.

335
00:25:20,666 --> 00:25:21,873
Your violin, Alphonse. Practise well.

336
00:25:22,624 --> 00:25:25,040
Practise to become a great musician.

337
00:25:25,208 --> 00:25:26,207
And if I don't?

338
00:25:26,374 --> 00:25:28,915
If you don't practise,

339
00:25:29,083 --> 00:25:30,707
you'll wind up a music critic.

340
00:25:31,083 --> 00:25:32,665
Watch out!

341
00:25:32,833 --> 00:25:33,998
It's leaving.

342
00:26:27,416 --> 00:26:31,790
I first saw Colette at a concert.
They were playing Berlioz.

343
00:26:31,958 --> 00:26:35,332
She sat five rows ahead of me, near the aisle.

344
00:26:35,499 --> 00:26:36,707
I spotted her immediately.

345
00:27:10,249 --> 00:27:12,832
I knew her name and address.
We'd even spoken.

346
00:27:12,999 --> 00:27:15,623
But I was nowhere. As I told my friend,

347
00:27:15,791 --> 00:27:17,623
"I've goofed on everything.

348
00:27:18,458 --> 00:27:20,290
"She's not even my type.

349
00:27:20,458 --> 00:27:22,998
"She talks like a boy, treats me like a pal.

350
00:27:23,166 --> 00:27:25,957
"When I'm being serious,
she just laughs at me.

351
00:27:27,416 --> 00:27:30,457
"Yet, I freeze my ass off waiting at her door."

352
00:27:31,833 --> 00:27:34,540
How do you know you're in love?

353
00:27:34,708 --> 00:27:36,832
When you become self-destructive.

354
00:27:36,999 --> 00:27:38,373
He may be right.

355
00:27:39,249 --> 00:27:42,540
We made a date for the following week.

356
00:27:42,708 --> 00:27:43,707
But the next day...

357
00:27:46,999 --> 00:27:48,873
Look who's here!

358
00:27:49,041 --> 00:27:50,457
What's up?

359
00:27:50,624 --> 00:27:53,998
I've got two seats to the lecture
on electronic music.

360
00:27:54,166 --> 00:27:57,207
I'm sorry. I've got homework this afternoon.

361
00:27:57,916 --> 00:27:59,207
How about a movie tonight?

362
00:27:59,374 --> 00:28:02,832
I can't. I must finish this work by tomorrow.

363
00:28:03,458 --> 00:28:04,582
I see.

364
00:28:05,333 --> 00:28:06,415
Can I come in?

365
00:28:06,583 --> 00:28:08,665
No, some other time. So long.

366
00:28:11,124 --> 00:28:12,790
Her father looked austere

367
00:28:12,958 --> 00:28:15,665
but I liked him at once.

368
00:28:15,833 --> 00:28:17,582
You still have your parents?

369
00:28:17,749 --> 00:28:20,082
Yes, but I never see them.

370
00:28:20,249 --> 00:28:21,873
We don't get along.

371
00:28:22,041 --> 00:28:23,290
What a shame.

372
00:28:23,958 --> 00:28:26,457
It must be hard on your mother.

373
00:28:26,874 --> 00:28:28,665
I guess it's my fault.

374
00:28:29,249 --> 00:28:31,623
I used to run away from home.

375
00:28:31,791 --> 00:28:34,415
- Colette wouldn't dare!
- Wanna bet!

376
00:28:35,458 --> 00:28:36,582
Well, for me, family. . .

377
00:28:36,708 --> 00:28:37,832
Question:

378
00:28:38,583 --> 00:28:40,915
Where is one
better off than with one's family?

379
00:28:41,083 --> 00:28:42,915
Answer: Anywhere else!

380
00:28:44,374 --> 00:28:45,998
I read that in a book.

381
00:28:47,458 --> 00:28:48,873
She's not like that.

382
00:28:49,041 --> 00:28:50,415
Don't be too sure.

383
00:28:50,583 --> 00:28:52,665
Can I have more wine?

384
00:28:53,916 --> 00:28:55,123
Me, too.

385
00:29:09,999 --> 00:29:12,873
Dear Antoine, Your love letter
is so eloquent.

386
00:29:13,041 --> 00:29:14,998
It suggests a man of experience.

387
00:29:15,958 --> 00:29:18,123
I'm going to hear Le Roux tonight.
Will you be there?

388
00:29:18,291 --> 00:29:19,748
Thanks for the books.

389
00:29:20,624 --> 00:29:22,707
My mother says you look romantic,

390
00:29:22,874 --> 00:29:24,665
probably because of your long hair.

391
00:29:24,833 --> 00:29:26,707
See you tonight. Colette.

392
00:29:28,708 --> 00:29:29,748
Colette?

393
00:29:29,958 --> 00:29:31,832
Yes, hello there.

394
00:29:32,499 --> 00:29:33,498
My poor head.

395
00:29:33,583 --> 00:29:36,665
Why didn't you show up? Were you sick?

396
00:29:36,833 --> 00:29:38,082
I said I might come.

397
00:29:38,249 --> 00:29:40,707
But some friends took me to a party.

398
00:29:40,874 --> 00:29:44,623
Real nuts. We carried on all night long.

399
00:29:44,791 --> 00:29:46,790
It was hilarious.

400
00:29:46,958 --> 00:29:49,457
But after a while, it got to be too wild.

401
00:29:50,208 --> 00:29:53,373
We wound up at, it must have been 5 a.m.

402
00:29:53,541 --> 00:29:55,540
Can I come by later on?

403
00:29:55,833 --> 00:29:57,123
If you like, but I may be out.

404
00:29:57,291 --> 00:30:00,832
We all said we'd try to meet again today.

405
00:30:02,374 --> 00:30:04,707
- See you later.
- You will if I'm in!

406
00:30:04,916 --> 00:30:07,957
I vowed to banish Colette from my life.

407
00:30:08,499 --> 00:30:10,373
I stood by my decision

408
00:30:10,541 --> 00:30:13,123
and refrained from contacting her.

409
00:30:15,083 --> 00:30:17,165
He's got some nerve.

410
00:30:19,499 --> 00:30:22,582
Fate decided otherwise:
her family moved and now lived

411
00:30:22,749 --> 00:30:24,748
right across the street from me.

412
00:30:35,416 --> 00:30:39,498
Christine was quite different
although she, too, was musical.

413
00:30:39,749 --> 00:30:42,832
She attended the Conservatory,
studied the violin.

414
00:30:44,041 --> 00:30:45,832
I'd known her several months.

415
00:30:45,999 --> 00:30:49,290
Seeing her behind a window
one day, I decided to marry her.

416
00:30:51,166 --> 00:30:52,332
I called her "Peggy Proper."

417
00:30:52,499 --> 00:30:54,790
"Peggy" for her British reserve.

418
00:30:54,958 --> 00:30:57,665
"Proper" because she was.

419
00:31:00,374 --> 00:31:03,207
Christine was always nicer to me
than I was to her.

420
00:31:05,458 --> 00:31:08,540
I forgot my handkerchief.
Can you lend me one?

421
00:31:08,708 --> 00:31:10,165
I've only got Kleenex.

422
00:31:10,333 --> 00:31:12,040
I never blow my nose in paper!

423
00:31:15,624 --> 00:31:18,332
- Well, so long.
- Where's your violin?

424
00:31:18,499 --> 00:31:20,123
I'm not giving a lesson.

425
00:31:20,291 --> 00:31:21,290
What, then?

426
00:31:21,416 --> 00:31:24,207
Do you always tell me where you go?

427
00:31:25,208 --> 00:31:26,707
See you tonight.

428
00:31:28,374 --> 00:31:30,873
DRESSMAKER - GYNAECOLOGlST -
NOTARY PUBLlC

429
00:32:07,499 --> 00:32:10,957
Dinner is served.
A gentleman is waiting for you.

430
00:32:11,124 --> 00:32:12,290
Really?

431
00:32:12,833 --> 00:32:15,748
Oh, yes, I'll be right there.

432
00:32:38,916 --> 00:32:42,748
Xavier, my love, I knew you'd come.
I hoped you would.

433
00:32:43,999 --> 00:32:47,040
Antoine, it's you ! I'm sorry.

434
00:32:47,249 --> 00:32:50,415
No, I'm sorry to disappoint you.

435
00:32:50,583 --> 00:32:52,457
Never mind.

436
00:32:52,624 --> 00:32:54,248
I saw you at the station.

437
00:32:54,416 --> 00:32:56,082
I never thought you'd be on this train.

438
00:32:56,249 --> 00:32:57,998
So good to see you.

439
00:32:58,333 --> 00:32:59,457
Same here.

440
00:32:59,624 --> 00:33:01,832
I'm really glad. I've got so much to tell you.

441
00:33:02,958 --> 00:33:04,748
Sit down.

442
00:33:09,666 --> 00:33:12,832
A surprise, but a nice one!

443
00:33:13,708 --> 00:33:15,915
What a strange day.

444
00:33:16,874 --> 00:33:18,415
I didn't mean to leave Paris.

445
00:33:18,499 --> 00:33:19,498
Really?

446
00:33:19,583 --> 00:33:21,123
But seeing you was a shock.

447
00:33:21,291 --> 00:33:22,415
A shock?

448
00:33:22,583 --> 00:33:25,165
An emotional shock. I had to see you.

449
00:33:25,333 --> 00:33:27,248
The train was pulling out. I jumped on.

450
00:33:28,041 --> 00:33:31,748
I don't even have a ticket!

451
00:33:32,374 --> 00:33:33,748
I can't believe it.

452
00:33:33,833 --> 00:33:34,957
Colette,

453
00:33:35,791 --> 00:33:37,457
I often think of you.

454
00:33:39,833 --> 00:33:42,873
How long has it been?

455
00:33:42,958 --> 00:33:44,082
Stop!

456
00:33:44,333 --> 00:33:47,498
No figures, no dates. We don't need that!

457
00:33:48,374 --> 00:33:52,707
We're just two people happy to meet again.

458
00:33:52,874 --> 00:33:56,082
I've already spent time with you today.

459
00:33:57,499 --> 00:34:01,123
It's embarrassing.
That book is over two years old.

460
00:34:01,833 --> 00:34:02,957
I've changed since.

461
00:34:03,333 --> 00:34:05,832
Don't forget, it's fiction.

462
00:34:05,999 --> 00:34:09,082
A bit autobiographical, but fiction.

463
00:34:09,249 --> 00:34:10,790
You said it!

464
00:34:10,958 --> 00:34:13,457
I just read that part about my family moving.

465
00:34:13,624 --> 00:34:15,123
Here's how it goes:

466
00:34:16,416 --> 00:34:18,457
"I vowed to banish Colette

467
00:34:18,624 --> 00:34:20,915
"from my life.

468
00:34:21,083 --> 00:34:22,957
"I stood by my decision

469
00:34:23,124 --> 00:34:25,873
"and refrained from contacting her again."

470
00:34:26,041 --> 00:34:27,082
Fair enough.

471
00:34:27,708 --> 00:34:32,123
"Fate decided otherwise: her family moved

472
00:34:32,374 --> 00:34:35,207
"and now lived right across the street

473
00:34:35,374 --> 00:34:36,540
"from me.

474
00:34:36,708 --> 00:34:39,373
"I couldn't turn down their invitations

475
00:34:39,541 --> 00:34:40,665
"without being rude."

476
00:34:40,833 --> 00:34:44,332
Sharp and well written, but it's a lie.

477
00:34:44,499 --> 00:34:46,123
A pack of lies.

478
00:34:46,291 --> 00:34:47,790
You gave up your room

479
00:34:47,958 --> 00:34:50,040
to move across the street from us.

480
00:34:50,708 --> 00:34:53,123
My parents were so surprised that day

481
00:34:53,291 --> 00:34:54,873
when we got home.

482
00:35:01,083 --> 00:35:02,498
Do you see what I see?

483
00:35:02,666 --> 00:35:03,748
It's Antoine!

484
00:35:04,208 --> 00:35:06,207
What a fantastic coincidence!

485
00:35:06,666 --> 00:35:08,582
What happened?

486
00:35:09,999 --> 00:35:11,665
Do you live here, now?

487
00:35:11,833 --> 00:35:12,915
Yes, I do.

488
00:35:13,083 --> 00:35:14,373
Since when?

489
00:35:14,541 --> 00:35:15,915
This afternoon !

490
00:35:20,124 --> 00:35:22,040
- Can we come up?
- Sure.

491
00:35:34,166 --> 00:35:37,290
He's all moved in !

492
00:35:45,291 --> 00:35:49,207
Fantastic! Hot and cold running water!

493
00:35:50,333 --> 00:35:52,915
You can see our windows.

494
00:35:54,499 --> 00:35:56,248
But the sun shines down on our side!

495
00:36:00,124 --> 00:36:02,040
You're right.

496
00:36:02,208 --> 00:36:04,998
But it worked better with the roles inverted.

497
00:36:05,083 --> 00:36:06,082
You don't say.

498
00:36:06,833 --> 00:36:08,498
And I merged several people

499
00:36:08,666 --> 00:36:10,373
into one character.

500
00:36:10,541 --> 00:36:12,748
I know all about creative devices.

501
00:36:12,916 --> 00:36:16,957
But I'm right in assuming
the girl from the Youth Concerts

502
00:36:17,124 --> 00:36:19,873
is in fact me?

503
00:36:22,041 --> 00:36:24,332
Let's get back to you.

504
00:36:24,791 --> 00:36:26,123
Are you married?

505
00:36:26,749 --> 00:36:28,665
Yesterday, the answer was "yes."

506
00:36:29,124 --> 00:36:31,748
I was married five years.
We separated three years ago.

507
00:36:31,916 --> 00:36:34,373
At least, for the first time.

508
00:36:35,458 --> 00:36:37,873
Our repeated separations
were more turbulent

509
00:36:38,041 --> 00:36:39,582
than our years together.

510
00:36:39,749 --> 00:36:42,915
An outsider can't presume to judge, but. . .

511
00:36:43,083 --> 00:36:47,248
Did you really try to save your marriage?

512
00:36:47,541 --> 00:36:49,373
No, on the contrary.

513
00:36:50,083 --> 00:36:51,123
In writing my book,

514
00:36:51,208 --> 00:36:54,748
the memories of my past
made me edgy, nasty.

515
00:36:55,916 --> 00:36:59,248
Christine was no help.
She disapproved of my work.

516
00:37:00,166 --> 00:37:02,748
So I started playing around

517
00:37:02,916 --> 00:37:05,332
to make up for
what I'd missed before my marriage.

518
00:37:05,791 --> 00:37:07,832
We had arguments every day.

519
00:37:07,999 --> 00:37:10,123
They led to our first separation.

520
00:37:17,291 --> 00:37:20,540
A taxi, please. 1 7, rue Decazes.

521
00:37:23,291 --> 00:37:26,082
Six minutes? Thank you.

522
00:37:26,999 --> 00:37:28,373
Going out?

523
00:37:28,541 --> 00:37:29,957
Yes I am.

524
00:37:30,124 --> 00:37:32,790
But you can stay here with Alphonse.

525
00:37:32,958 --> 00:37:35,373
- There's food.
- I'll walk you down.

526
00:37:36,333 --> 00:37:39,040
Good night, be good !

527
00:37:43,166 --> 00:37:44,915
Watch TV if you like.

528
00:37:45,083 --> 00:37:47,540
Take care of him.

529
00:37:51,583 --> 00:37:53,207
This Balthus is yours.

530
00:37:53,374 --> 00:37:56,165
I gave it to you.

531
00:37:56,333 --> 00:37:58,165
It's yours!

532
00:38:10,083 --> 00:38:11,957
Remember how you used to say,

533
00:38:12,124 --> 00:38:16,040
"I'm taking my keys in case we fight!"

534
00:38:19,583 --> 00:38:21,582
You're in good spirits.

535
00:38:21,749 --> 00:38:22,748
Why not?

536
00:38:22,916 --> 00:38:25,082
I know whenever you come to see the baby,

537
00:38:25,291 --> 00:38:28,123
you expect me to give you hell. Right?

538
00:38:28,374 --> 00:38:29,623
